[4] Saudi Arabia: MOH advises against direct contact with camels -- media report
Date: Wed 30 Apr 2014
Source: Saudi Gazette [summ., edited]
http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20140430203585


Acting health minister Adel Fakeih said a group of Western experts and representatives of the World Health Organization (WHO) have met for 2 days in Riyadh to discuss "a series of preventive measures... to contain the spread" of MERS.

"These measures will be announced in the coming days," Fakeih told reporters.

He announced that the ministry started implementing an urgent plan to understand and analyze the nature of coronavirus and exploring the best ways to contain it.

The minister warned people against direct contact with camels. There should be extra care while handling raw meat of camel, and its milk should be consumed only after boiling, the minister said while adding that cooked meat poses no danger.

Fakeih has appointed a council of medical advisors with extensive experience in infectious diseases to help combat the MERS in the Kingdom. The 10-member council will work under Dr Prof Tariq Ahmed Madani who was appointed last week [week of 21 Apr 2014] as a special adviser to the ministry.

Last week, the WHO announced its readiness to send international experts to Saudi Arabia to investigate "any evolving risk" associated with the transmission pattern of the virus. MERS is considered a deadlier but less-transmissible cousin of the SARS virus that erupted in Asia in 2003.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[According to the Saudi MOH website, there have now been 361 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection including 107 deaths confirmed in Saudi Arabia since the virus was 1st identified in a case that died in June 2012.

Each of the daily reports on new laboratory confirmed infections with MERS-CoV now contains a map showing the geographic distribution of cases and deaths reported in Saudi Arabia in the 24 hours covered by the report, as well as graphs by type of facility (public, private, or home isolation), by age and health status, and by gender. These can be seen at the source URLs provided for items [1] and [2] above.

The press releases and media report above suggest that there is a major effort ongoing to interrupt transmission of the MERS-CoV in Saudi Arabia, both in terms of the nosocomial transmission that is apparently occurring in Jeddah, Riyadh, and now Tabuk, and the possible interspecies transmission that may well be occurring between humans and camels. The MOH announcement to avoid direct contact with camels is a significant step as camels are a major part of everyday life in the region. - Mod.MPP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2437089,131.]
